<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-001-728  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 001 728.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 25 1989 v6 n51 p35(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Low-cost LineLock upgrade steps up modem security. (communicationssoftware) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miles, J.B.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>LineLock 2.0 from Crystal Point Inc is an enhanced version ofcommunications software that provides better modem security for anunlimited number of modems on a network.andP;  LineLock has variouslevels of security through password protection and dial-backscreening of modems.andP;  LineLock keeps a database of all authorizednetwork users, workstations and external resources available.andP;  Thenew version of LineLock offers better modem security for abouthalf the cost of the original version.andP;  LineLock, $995 for afour-port license, $1,350 for an eight-port license and $1,995 fora 16-port license, can also monitor all secured modems remotelywith its integrated console program.andP;  Crystal Point offers a'slave' version of the communications software that lets userscrate separate modem pools.andP;  Prices for the slave version rangefrom $1,245 to $2,245.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Crystal Point Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   LineLock 2.0 (Communications software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Communications softwareSoftware packagesProduct IntroductionSecurity Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By J.B.andP;  MilesandM;Crystal Point Inc. plans to announce on Jan.andP;  5 a new version of its LineLockcommunications software that company officials said provides better modemsecurity for half the price of the original package.andM;LineLock version 2.0 now includes the ability for multiple modem servers toshare the same network database and to remotely monitor the network's modempool, officials from the Bothell, Wash., company said last week.andM;While the original LineLock software was limited to 16 modems on the network,the new release supports a virtually unlimited number of modems on a network,according to Fred Stephens, vice president of research and development atCrystal Point.andM;&quot;LineLock grows with a network's need and gives administrators the ability toexpand the network modem pool accordingly,&quot; he said.andM;LineLock provides various levels of network security through passwordprotection and dial-back screening of the network's modems.andP;  The programmaintains a database of all authorized network users, workstations andavailable external resources.andP;  It also provides an audit trail of all modemsused on the network and automatically hangs up idle lines.andM;Remote monitoring of all secured modems is now possible through the new,integrated console program in LineLock 2.0, which allows database maintenanceto be performed anywhere on the network, according to Chris Stephens,president of Crystal Point.andM;The firm is also offering a new &quot;slave&quot; version of the software that enablesusers to create separate modem pools in outlying areas of the network.andM;The LineLock slave software passes the user's modem-access requests across abridge to another LineLock system for database searching and validation.andM;&quot;The access to a remote database significantly increases access time overwide area networks,&quot; Fred Stephens said.andM;LineLock version 2.0, available now, costs $995 for a four-port license,$1,350 for an eight-port license and $1,995 for a 16-port license.andM;The slave version, also available now, is priced at $1,245 for a four-portlicense, $1,500 for an eight-port license and $2,245 for a 16-port license.andM;Crystal Point can be reached at (206) 487-3656.andM;----------Additional reporting by Tara Sexton</TEXT></DOC>